As noted in the attached editorial by Pediatrician Donald Berwick, it is time to readjust our thinking about how we can best provide healthcare for all Americans and stop the current fear-mongering around "Medicare for All" type plans.https://t.co/ryRLtuuDIC

The current system leaves out millions of people and running a business has enough worries on its own without adding additional burdens and expenses to these businesses of trying to cover their workers with healthcare.
As a Democratic candidate in New Jersey's 11th Congressional District, I support moving toward a "Medicare for All" system. Relying on employers to provide health coverage to us is broken.

I agree with Mr. Blow that, "The impeachment inquiry needs to remain open after the Ukraine affair, not only to allow the cases in the courts to be resolved, but also to allow future whistle-blowers‚Äô information to be immediately considered in the context of impeachment."

"There was talk of another impeachment article, to be written by Thaddeus Stevens, health permitting, but Stevens was growing more feeble every day" (Wineapple, Brenda, The Impeachers: The Trail of Andrew Johnson and the Dream of a Just Nation, Random House, 2019, p. 384).
Secondly, another House impeachment article was considered (but not acted upon) after President Andrew Johnson was acquitted by just one vote in his 1868 Senate impeachment trial.
First off, I agree with Mr. Blow that "There is nothing in the Constitution that prevents a president from being impeached more than once."

https://t.co/3pbsJ8e2hQ There is some historical evidence to back this OP-ED piece by Charles M. Blow in today's New York Times that impeachment does not have to end with the first acquittal in a Senate Trial.
